2.	LITERATURE REVIEW
2.1.	Telematics in Fleet Safety
Telematics systems have become ubiquitous in commercial fleets, providing real-time data on vehicle location, speed, engine performance, and driver behavior (Giannotti et al., 2020). Research has demonstrated that tTelematics-based driver coaching can reduce harsh braking events by 30-50% and & speeding incidents by 20-40% (Johnson & Brown, 2021). However, most existing applications focus on retrospective driver scoring rather than predictive risk assessment.

2.2.	Machine Learning for Incident Prediction
Recent advances in machine learning have shown promise in safety analytics. Studies utilizing Random Forest and Gradient Boosting models have achieved AUC-ROC scores between 0.70-0.85 for traffic incident prediction (Chen et al., 2022). Key predictors consistently identified include:
- Speeding events (strongest predictor)
- Harsh braking frequency
- Time of day (rush hour correlation)
- Weather conditions
- Vehicle maintenance history

2.3.	Driver Behavior Analysis
Driver behavior is a critical factor in fleet safety. Research by Martinez et al. (2021) identified that 70% of commercial vehicle incidents are behavior-related, with distraction and fatigue being primary contributors. Harsh acceleration events correlate with a 2.5x increase in incident probability, while combined speeding and & braking events elevate risk by 4x.

2.4.	Imbalanced Data in Safety Analytics
Safety incident data is inherently imbalanced, with incident rates typically ranging from 2-5% in commercial fleets. Scholars recommend using SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique) combined with cost-sensitive learning to address this challenge (Wang & Lee, 2020). F1-Score and & AUC-ROC are preferred over accuracy for model evaluation in such contexts.

2.5.	Business Applications
The insurance industry has begun adopting predictive analytics for Usage-Based Insurance (UBI) and & risk-based pricing (Patel et al., 2023). Fleets implementing proactive safety programs report:
- 15-25% reduction in collision frequency
- 20-30% decrease in claim costs
- 10-15% improvement in driver retention

2.6.	Research Gap
Despite the availability of telematics data and ML techniques, tThere is limited research on integrated frameworks that combine incident prediction, claim estimation, and driver segmentation in a single actionable system. This project bridges that gap by delivering a unified predictive safety analytics framework with clear business implementation pathways.

